WindowTitle->"RandomWickCircuit",
Visible->True,
TaggingRules->{
 "ModificationHighlight" -> False, "ColorType" -> "", "LinkTrails" -> "", 
  "ExampleCounter" -> 1, 
  "Openers" -> {
   "PrimaryExamplesSection" -> Open, "ExampleSection" -> {"0" -> Open}, 
    "AllOptsTable" -> Closed, "NotesSection" -> Closed}, "NewStyles" -> True, 
  "CitationPopupData" -> $Failed, "ShowCitation" -> False, "HasOptions" -> 
  True, "RootCaptions" -> "", "HeaderCoreAreaLink" -> {}, 
  "Metadata" -> {
   "built" -> "{2026, 2, 23, 15, 52, 57.176104}", 
    "history" -> {"14.3", "", "", ""}, "context" -> "QuantumMob`Q3`", 
    "keywords" -> {
     "fermionic quantum computation", "fermionic Gaussian state"}, 
    "specialkeywords" -> {}, "tutorialcollectionlinks" -> {}, "index" -> True,
     "label" -> "Quantum Mob/ Q3 Symbol", "language" -> "en", "paclet" -> 
    "QuantumMob/Q3", "status" -> "None", "summary" -> 
    "RandomWickCircuit[{uni, p}, dep] generates a random quantum circuit on \
non-interacting fermion modes, where layers of unitary or non-unitary gate \
uni (WickUnitary[...] or WickNonunitary) alternate with layers of \
measurements (WickMeasurement[...]) on fermion modes selected randomly with \
probability p to form an overall depth dep. RandomWickCircuit[{uspec, mspec}, \
dep] generates the unitary or non-unitary layer by RandomWickUnitary[uspec] \
or RandomWickNonunitary[uspec], respectively, and the measurement layer by \
RandomWickMeasurement[mspec]. RandomWickCircuit[{ham, pdf, p}, k] \
(**deprecated**) unitary layers of random unitary gate uni=Exp[-I ham \
\\[Tau]] with single-particle Hamiltonian ham ( n*n Hermitian matrix or \
WickHermitian[...]) and the random evolution time \\[Tau] distributed \
according to the probability distribution function pdf. \
RandomWickCircuit[{ham, p}, dep] assumes that the evolution time is uniformly \
distributed over the interval [0,2\\[Pi] n/max], where max is the maximum of \
the absolute values of the entries of ham. RandomWickCircuit[ham, dep] \
generates a circuit for n fermion modes where each unitary layer corresponds \
to time evolution U := exp(-I ham \\[Tau]) with the evolution time \\[Tau] \
distributed by the exponential distribution function \
P(\\[Tau])\\[Proportional]exp[-n \\[Tau]] and each measurement layer measures \
a fermion mode with probability p=1/n.", "synonyms" -> {}, "tabletags" -> {}, 
    "title" -> "RandomWickCircuit", "titlemodifier" -> "", "metadescription" -> 
    "", "windowtitle" -> "RandomWickCircuit", "type" -> "Symbol", "uri" -> 
    "QuantumMob/Q3/ref/RandomWickCircuit"}},
